 explored throughout expose stereotypes and biases against women in unusual positions of power, which were embedded in the motif and persisted in Western European art.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDragons in art. 0aWomen in artxHistoryyTo 1500. 4aArt and Material Culture. 4aDiachronic. 4aGender and Sexuality Studies. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 7aART / History / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aWomen, Dragon, Art, Witch, Sacred.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAmsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311102374840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9789048555505?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789048555505423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789048555505/original  a978-3-11-102374-8  Amsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles